            <abstract>
                <p>This astrological text contains descriptions of the twelve zodiac signs, including their position in the sky, appearance, astrological characteristics, and corresponding periods. 
                    Each description of a zodiac sign concludes with a separate section on women. According to <bibl>
                        <ptr target="bm:Neugebauer1979Astronomy"></ptr>
                        <citedRange unit="page">162</citedRange>
                    </bibl>, the mathematical operation required for identification of a corresponding zodiac sign is a reduction modulo 12 of the numerical equivalents of a person's name 
                    and the name of the mother, that is a divisian by 12 with a remainder. The remainder is the parameter which defines the corresponding zodiacal sign.
                    The text demonstrates a fairly stable structure, but there is some variability in wording across different manuscripts. All zodiac names are transliterated from Arabic. In <ref type="mss" corresp="EMIP02288"></ref>, 
                    the text contains a short, almost illegible, note on the purpose and possibly the authorship of the text.</p>
            </abstract>
